and dissemination of radical ideas in the period by focusing on actors ('radical voices') and a variety of written texts and cultural practices ('radical ways'), ranging from fiction, correspondence, pamphlets and newspapers to petitions presented to Parliament and toasts raised in public. They analyse the way these media interacted with their political, religious, social and literary context. This volume provides an interdisciplinary outlook on the study of early modern radicalism,with contributions from literary scholars and historians, and uses case studies as insights into the global picture of radical ideas. It will be of interest to students of seventeenth- and eighteenth-century literature and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRadicalism and the pressxHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aRadicalism and the pressxHistoryx18th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aRadicalism and the presszGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aRadicalism and the presszGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 0aRadicalism in literaturexGreat Britain. 0aRadicalism in literature. 0aRadicalismxHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aRadicalismxHistoryx18th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aRadicalismzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aRadicalismzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  acultural transfers.  aeighteenth century.  aprint culture.  aradicalism.  aseventeenth century.1 aCavaillé, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurelly, Laurent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurelly, Laurent, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuthille, Rémy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Catie, econtributor.4ctb4https://